        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>geotag</strong> is a <strong>location label attached to a social media post, photo, or video</strong> that identifies where the content was created or is relevant to. It appears as a clickable location name at the top of the post and adds the post to that location's public feed on Instagram, TikTok, Facebook, and other platforms.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Engagement lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">+79% on Instagram</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Platforms</div>
            <div class="tms-value">IG, TikTok, FB, YT</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The geotag is the quiet workhorse of local social marketing. It costs nothing, takes two taps, and it doubles the surfaces where your content can be discovered.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a geotag?</h2>
        <p>A geotag is a metadata label — usually the name of a city, neighbourhood, business, or venue — that a creator attaches to a post at the time of publishing. On most platforms, tapping the geotag opens a location feed showing all public posts tagged at that place, ranked by recency and engagement.</p>
        <p>Geotags are different from the underlying GPS coordinates baked into an image file (that's <a href="/glossary/geotagging-images/">image geotagging</a>). They're also different from a virtual advertising boundary (that's <a href="/glossary/geofencing/">geofencing</a>).</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">How platforms pick the geotag database</div>
          <p>Instagram, TikTok, and Facebook all share Meta's Places database, which is seeded by Facebook Pages and Foursquare. When a business creates a Facebook Page, its address becomes an instant tagable location across the Meta ecosystem.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why geotags matter</h2>
        <p>Four reasons a good social media manager never skips the geotag:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Local discovery.</strong> People browse location feeds when they're planning to visit or trying to see what's happening at a venue. Your post appears there for free.</li>
          <li><strong>Engagement lift.</strong> Instagram posts with a location tag get 79% more engagement than untagged posts (Later.com, 2024).</li>
          <li><strong>Local SEO signal reinforcement.</strong> Consistent tagging of your business location across Meta reinforces the entity for Google's Knowledge Graph.</li>
          <li><strong>Event visibility.</strong> Conference venues, sports arenas, and festivals become audience pools. Attendees browsing the venue tag see your content.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How geotagging works</h2>
        <p>Three mechanisms drive a geotag onto a post.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># 1. Automatic detection</span><br>
          device: <span class="uf-status">location services on</span><br>
          platform suggests: <span class="uf-new">"Coffee Shop, Brooklyn"</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 2. Manual selection</span><br>
          creator taps: <span class="uf-label">Add location</span><br>
          searches: "Times Square"<br>
          selects from list<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 3. Location page aggregation</span><br>
          all public posts with same tag → <span class="uf-new">location feed</span><br>
          discoverable via search + explore
        </div>

