        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real geotag examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Neighborhood cafe — every post tagged</h3>
        <p>A local coffee shop tags every Instagram post with its business location. Tourists searching "Brooklyn cafes" via location filter discover 60% of new customers through the location feed alone. Zero paid spend.</p>

        <h3>2. Multi-location dental practice</h3>
        <p>A group with six offices tags each post with the specific office location rather than a generic city. Local patients see reviews and behind-the-scenes clips for the closest office, driving 3x higher new-patient consult bookings vs. untagged content.</p>

        <h3>3. B2B SaaS at a conference</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># SaaS company posts from SaaStr Annual</span><br>
          tag: <span class="uf-new">"San Jose Convention Center"</span><br>
          content: <span class="uf-status">live demo clip</span><br>
          reach: attendees browsing venue tag → 4x normal event engagement
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Geotag vs hashtag — which one</h2>
        <p>Both are discovery surfaces. They optimise different things.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Geotag wins for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Local discovery of physical businesses</li>
              <li>Event-based reach at venues</li>
              <li>Reinforcing a business entity's geography</li>
              <li>Restaurants, cafes, retail, tourism</li>
              <li>Location-planning-mode searchers</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Hashtag wins for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Topic-based discovery across geographies</li>
              <li>Community-based reach (#foodie, #saas)</li>
              <li>Trend participation</li>
              <li>Broad content categorisation</li>
              <li>Non-location-specific brands</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for geotags</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Always tag your business location.</strong> Every organic post from your brand account should carry your location, even if the photo isn't literally at the office.</li>
          <li><strong>Use specific venue tags, not city tags.</strong> "Blue Bottle Coffee — Williamsburg" beats "Brooklyn" for intent quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up your Facebook Page first.</strong> That's what creates a clean, canonical Meta Places entry for Instagram to pull.</li>
          <li><strong>Tag events during the event, not after.</strong> The venue location feed spikes in real time — post while people are searching it.</li>
          <li><strong>Combine with local hashtags.</strong> Geotag captures location searchers; #brooklyn captures topic browsers. Do both.</li>
          <li><strong>Encourage UGC tagging.</strong> Signage in your venue that shows the exact location tag turns customers into free reach.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — tagging locations you're not at</div>
          <p>Tagging Times Square from a post shot in New Jersey looks spammy to the algorithm and dilutes real location data. Meta has been cracking down on obvious mismatches since 2023 with reduced feed reach for location-inconsistent posts.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common geotag mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skipping the tag entirely</strong> — half the discovery surface, thrown away.</li>
          <li><strong>Only tagging the city, never the venue</strong> — misses the intent-heavy searches.</li>
          <li><strong>Tagging locations you didn't visit</strong> — dilutes signals and risks reduced reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent tagging across accounts</strong> — five brand accounts, five different location entries, zero cumulative signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring stories and reels</strong> — the Stories location sticker is a separate, high-discovery surface.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps with geotags</h2>
        <p>theStacc's Social module lets multi-location brands schedule content with the correct per-location geotag automatically — so a franchise with 30 outlets doesn't rely on individual managers to remember. Reports show engagement lift attributable to consistent geotagging alongside the rest of your local SEO signals.</p>

